    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism is fundamentally a conservative approach that insists the Constitution's meaning is fixed at the time of its ratification, preventing future generations from rewriting the document to suit their own political agendas. Proponents argue that this method preserves democratic legitimacy by ensuring the framers' intent governs, rather than allowing unelected judges to impose their personal policy preferences under the guise of interpretation. By strictly adhering to the text and historical context, originalism acts as a crucial check on judicial overreach and protects minority rights from the tyranny of the majority. Ultimately, it is the only way to maintain a stable, predictable legal system that respects the foundational agreement made by the people.",
      "source": "target",
